quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Show/Hide[/h1]

jQuery has some easy-to-implement effects to create animations.
The [b]hide[/b]() and [b]show[/b]() methods are used to hide and show the selected elements.
The [b]toggle[/b]() method is used to toggle between hiding and showing elements.
For example: [code format="js" codeId="1135"]$(function() {
  $("p").click(function() {
    $("div").[b]toggle[/b]();
  });
});[/code]
The hide/show/toggle methods can take an optional argument, speed, which specifies the animation speed in [b]milliseconds[/b].
For example, let's pass 1000 millisecond as the speed argument to the toggle() method: [code format="js" codeId="1136"]$(function() {
  $("p").click(function() {
    $("div").toggle([b]1000[/b]);
  });
});[/code]
[note]The hide/show/toggle methods can also take a second optional parameter [b]callback[/b], which is a function to be executed after the animation completes.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to fade the paragraph to 60% opacity in 2 seconds.
[!raw!]
$("p").fadeTo({0}, {1});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Fade In/Out[/h1]

Similar to the hide/show methods, jQuery provides the [b]fadeIn[/b]/[b]fadeOut [/b]methods, which fade an element in and out of visibility. 
Just like the [b]toggle[/b]() method switches between hiding and showing, the  [b]fadeToggle[/b]() method fades in and out.
Let's see [b]fadeToggle[/b]() in action: [code format="js" codeId="1137"]$(function() {
  $("p").click(function() {
    $("div").[b]fadeToggle[/b](1000);
  });
});[/code]
Just like toggle(), fadeToggle() takes two optional parameters: [b]speed [/b]and [b]callback[/b].
[note]Another method used for fading is [b]fadeTo[/b](), which allows fading to a given opacity (value between 0 and 1). For example: $("div").fadeTo(1500, 0.7);[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to slide down the div element in 3 seconds upon clicking on the paragraph.
[!raw!]
$("p").{0}(function() {
  {1}("div").slideDown({2});
});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Slide Up/Down[/h1]

The [b]slideUp[/b]() and [b]slideDown[/b]() methods are used to create a sliding effect on elements.
Again, similar to the previous toggle methods, the [b]slideToggle[/b]() method switches between the sliding effects and can take two optional parameters: speed and callback.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="js" codeId="1138"]$(function() {
  $("p").click(function() {
    $("div").[b]slideToggle[/b](500);
  });
});[/code]
